entry.title: Fix presubmit error for expired virtual test suites
entry.content:
There are presubmit checks to ensure virtual baselines/expectations are

deleted once a VTS is deleted. With the introduction of expiry dates for

virtual suites, this can be triggered once a VTS expired.



Do not trigger such presubmit check error on an expired VTS. Delay

that to when the VTS is actually deleted from the json file.



For expired VTSs, plan to have a service to automatically delete

them after some amount of time.

entry.title: Clipboard: remove user activation requirement for reading web custom formats
entry.content:
Before this change, we required both transient user activation and

read/write permissions to read content from the clipboard using the

read() method for web custom formats.



Checking for transient user activation seems redundant because user already has control over the read/write permissions. Moreover, it breaks remote clipboard read scenarios.



When the permission has been granted, a user activation should not also be required. This brings web custom formats into alignment with the behavior for standard formats like plain text.

entry.title: Fix under-invalidation when dynamically adding aria-describedby nodes
entry.content:
When an element with aria-describedby is added, we should call

AXRelationCache::UpdateReverseTextRelations to add the list

of ids referenced by aria-describedby, so that if elements receive

that id in the future, the description can be noted in the a11y tree.



This wasn't working unless there was already at least one node already

in the tree at the time the aria-describedby element is processed.

Now we call AXRelationCache::UpdateReverseTextRelations always,

which will fill in id_attr_to_text_relation_mapping_ with a key for

each attribute and an empty set value. This allows subsequent code

adding elements with those ids to notice that they should invalidate

the aria-describedby element.



In addition to the testcase in this CL, this fixes a source of

flakiness in CL 4553316.

entry.title: Evict results when HostResolverCache exceeds size limit
entry.content:
Behavior diverges from the legacy HostCache implementation in that,

instead of only ever evicting one entry at a time, on reaching the size

limit, HostResolverCache will evict all stale entries, only doing a

single-entry expiration if all are non-stale. This is an attempt at a

performance optimization because eviction requires iterating *all*

cache contents to find the oldest entry. Therefore once it reaches max

size, legacy HostCache would have to do a full-cache iteration every

time a result is added.



Also, no longer allow the legacy HostCache behavior that a zero size limit could be used to denote a disabled cache. Instead DCHECK that the limit is always at least one, and if something wants to disable caching, don't create the cache object. Not aware of anything left in Chrome creating the cache with zero size, so the functionality just doesn't seem necessary.



Also, skip the cache pinning functionality from legacy HostCache that allowed nonevictable entries. The functionality is unnecessary because it was created for a feature that ended up never using it.

entry.title: Re-add dep on AccessibilityManager in WebContentsAccessibilityImpl
entry.content:
The CL at crrev.com/c/4569293 made a change to isAccessibilityEnabled()

that may lead to a race condition while returning the most updated value

as per AccessibilityState.isAnyAccessibilityServiceEnabled().



AccessibilityState needs to update its fields via

AccessibilityState#updateAccessibilityServices. If

WebContentsAccessibilityImpl#isAccessibilityEnabled is called before

AccessibilityState#updateAccessibilityServices finishes updating its

fields, then the incorrect state may be returned.

we should be returning the node info. This may have lead to an increase

in crashes in the Android framework that was expecting a node. The

relevant line in the Android framework at

ViewRootImpl#findFocusedVirtualNode also separately needed a null check

to avoid crashes.

entry.title: Ensures high-res timer in DesktopCaptureDevice on Windows
entry.content:
Today it is not guaranteed that the capture timer

(using base::OneShotTimer) in the DesktopCaptureDevice runs at a

high enough resolution to capture at the requested capture rate.



Local tests have shown that asking for 30 fps using [1] often leads

to ~22 fps (for both WGC and DXGI) instead and it can cause a high

rate of RequestRefreshFrame calls from sinks that does not get what

they ask for.



The root cause for this deviation is illustrated by the logs in [2].

We need a delta time of e.g. N ms, but the actual delta time instead

becomes N + ~15 ms which corresponds to the lowest timer resolution

on Windows (1/64 sec). As a result, the actual rate will differ from

what the client asks for in AllocateAndStart.



[3] also shows that a rate of ~22 is very common and the most

probable cause is that these users have hit the same problem since

the default frame rate for getDisplayMedia is 30 fps.



In Canary, we often see ~30 fps but not always and it seems almost

random if our process (the Browser process) is running in a high-

resolution mode or not. It can also depends on what other APIs are

used by additional Chrome Tabs.



This CL ensures that the DCD always asks for high-res timers on

Windows to ensure that the requested frame rate is correct and that

spam RRFs are avoided. If base::Time::IsHighResolutionTimerInUse()

returns true, nothing extra is done.



It is expected that the ~22 fps mode in [3] will decrease after this

change.



It is also possible to ask for a higher resolution by using

timeBeginPeriod/timeEndPeriod APIs directly. That way we could also

ask for e.g 125 or 250 Hz instead of 1000 Hz as today. I have done

local power measurements where I've compared the average power

consumption and found no significant difference between 125, 250 or

1000 Hz. Also, using Time::ActivateHighResolutionTimer ensures that

the resolution is set correctly given if AC or DC is used or not.

And its is the API that the main HighResolutionTimerManager use.



This CL will be a NOP in all cases where we already today support

high-resolution, and in those that we don't, the requested frame rate

will be correct. It might come with a cost in power but that is only

because we now provide what the client asks for and not due to this

change as such (we can't compare ~22 with 30 fps).



[1] https://henrik-and.github.io/gdm/

[2] https://paste.googleplex.com/5648058518863872

[3] https://screenshot.googleplex.com/3LWsgCNDmGUmGVB

entry.title: Change preference api tests to run with shared ash.
entry.content:
ExtensionPreferenceApiLacrosBrowserTest supposes to test

chrome.accessibilityFeatures which controls a11y feature

pref in ash via extension api. However, AccessibilityController

(run in ash) will pop up an confirmation dialog when

some a11y feature pref changes(eg autoclick), and the dialog

is not closed after the test tears down and will affect other

lacros browser tests running after it. So the test runs with

unique ash to avoid such issue. This cl fixes the problem by

changing the pref to be tested to spokenFeedback, which

will not cause a visual confirmation dialog to pop up, so that

the test can run with shared ash.

entry.title: Re-enable CPU Profiling trace event tests
entry.content:
The test was disabled because it used to rely on trace events

dispatched by V8 only when runtime call stats were enabled, which caused

issues to the V8 folks when they worked on disabling RCS on stable

builds [1] [2] [3]. As a result the test was removed to allow for

landing the disabling CL



This CL adds the test back but removes the problematic trace event

which relied on RCS being enabled, namely "V8.Execute". I've tried

successfully running the test with RCS off (by toggling the flag at [4])

with these changes in place



[1] https://bugs.chromium.org/p/v8/issues/detail?id=12405

[2] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1KvkBqt-uxwWuxf-UATt_-ZEydIj7VtDq7zaVyWAzeVc/edit#

entry.title: gpu: Make legacy NV12 images work for Graphite Dawn
entry.content:
https://crrev.com/c/4582472 was meant to make legacy NV12 shared images

work with SkiaGraphiteDawnImageRepresentation, but it didn't resolve the

issue completely - we still see Dawn validation errors due to texture

usage being incorrectly specified for per-plane shared images since it's

not possible to distinguish between R8/RG8 as YUV planes vs R8/RG8

single plane images.



This CL addresses that by:



1) GetGraphiteTextureInfo, GetSupportedDawnTextureUsage, etc. take an

additional `is_yuv_plane` parameter that specifies if a single plane

format corresponds to a plane of a legacy multi-planar format image.



2) Both IOSurfaceImageBacking and D3DImageBacking check the underlying

texture format to compute the correct value for `is_yuv_plane`.



3) DawnIOSurfaceRepresentation uses the IOSurface size in the Dawn

texture descriptor, otherwise the UV plane import fails validation.



Other minor fixes:



1) D3DImageBacking caches the D3D11_TEXTURE2D_DESC since it's used in

many places including for computing `is_yuv_plane`. Similarly, the

IOSurfaceImageBacking caches IOSurface format and size.



2) ToDawnFormat/ToWGPUFormat have two variants - one that can return a

multi-planar format and one which returns single plane formats only.

entry.title: Make the CSS parser fast paths reject “123.” style doubles.
entry.content:
Use the same ParseDouble() function (now renamed to

ParsePositiveDouble(), as it does not deal with negative numbers)

for all double parsing in the CSS parser fast paths, instead of

CharactersToDouble(), which allows some numbers that are not allowed

by the CSS spec.



Note that this has two side effects:



- Accuracy may go down, as ParsePositiveDouble() only supports six

digits after the decimal point (the rest are consumed but ignored).

We mitigate this somewhat by going from six to seven, fixing some

tests (but not all; we have to write new results into

svg/dom/length-list-parser.html, which at some point parses

subnormal numbers).

- The fast paths now reject scientific notation (e.g. 123e3) too;

such numbers will fall back to the slow path.



Fixed: 841960

entry.title: [aw] Add a feature to reset the draw functor in background.
entry.content:
When a WebView becomes invisible, the tiles required for the next frame

are still retained, for as long as the WebView is alive. In particular,

unlocked compositor frame reclaim doesn't work for WebView, contrary to

Chrome.



In practice, this means that we retain ~17MiB of tiles for each

fullscreen WebView which exists on a given device at a time (for a 1440p

device, here on Pixel 6 Pro). A solution to not keep this memory is to

release the draw functor after some time in background. This triggers a

context destroyed notification (DrawFn_OnContextDestroyed), resulting in

SkiaOutputSurfaceImpl getting destroyed, and then all tiles being

released.
